Set up

library(tidyverse)
library(tidyr)
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)
library(hunspell)
sample <- read_csv("/Users/olivia/Documents/GitHub/hnyc_census/1880/census_1880_h_bk_sample100k.csv")
names(sample) <- c("record", "year", "dwelling_ser", "dwsize", "township", "pageno", "microfilm", "n_fam", "hh_ser_bef_split", "split", "mcd", "county", "ED", "supdist", "street" )
sample <- extract(sample, "street", c("house_num", "street_add"), "(\\d.)(\\D+)")

House numbers and street names are separated from the original address column, into house_num and street_add.

Dataset

Here is a sample of the 1880 Brooklyn census data. Variable names are now aligned with 1910 data.

Variables

Heres a demonstration of the possible misspellings in the 1880 Brooklyn data, which is representative of the whole dataset. According to the results, about 200 misspellings are detected in the data. Please note that it is possible that some detected words are correctly spelled, such as albany, york, MELROSE. A closer look into the street dictionaries will be needed to further clean the street names.

household1 <- filter(sample, record == "H")

mispellings <- household1$street_add %>%
  str_split(pattern = " ") %>%
  unlist() %>%
  unique()

hunspell(mispellings) %>% unlist() %>% unique()

Fill down options

An exploration of fill down using household persons to join addresses. Same attempt was made for 1910 data.

na_street <- which(is.na(household1$street_add))
na_street_1 <- na_street - 1
na_street <- c(na_street, na_street_1) %>% 
  unique() %>% 
  sort()

House Numbers

Here is a summary of the house numbers and street names in the sample data. There are 15519 entries with empty house numbers and street names and 116471 households with complete addresses. Also, some of the house numbers contain or only contain punctuations, which will be cleaned in later processes.

none only_house only_street both
